Dr. Victoria Greer Superintendent of Schools
Ms. Elizabeth Murphy Assistant Superintendent
Dr. Angela Burke Director of Curriculum
Ms. Jessica Murphy Director of Student Services
Ms. Nerlande Mintor Business Manager Director of Human Resources

Ms. Meg Dussualt Director of Fine Arts & Community Education
75 Mountain Street Sharon, MA 02067 Tel: 781.784.1570 Fax:781.784.1573

March 22,, 2020
Dear Sharon School Community,
The past week has been very challenging for our community as the number of COVID-19 cases within the state continue to rise. As you are aware, the Governor has required that all Massachusetts Public Schools are closed through April 6, 2020. The Department of Elementary and Secondary Education (DESE) advised that districts treat the first week (March 16-20) of closures the same as a snow day/week closure. As a result, last week, various resources were shared with students, parents and families to engage students during this time.
The district administration has worked collaboratively with the Curriculum Coordinators and school Principals to develop enrichment learning templates for students for this week. Teachers are eager to support students during this time and will continue to collaborate with their building principals and the curriculum coordinators to support students during the closure period. This week teachers will begin reaching out to their students in an effort to check-in and keep learning alive. Our efforts in keeping learning alive reflects the explicit direction districts across the state have received from the Massachusetts Commissioner of Elementary and Secondary Education.
We realize that the enrichment resources can not replace the level of education that students receive in a traditional brick and mortar building with the in-person experiences and interactions that our schools provide. To that end, we remain committed to our core values; H-E-A-R-T (Honesty, Equity, Acceptance, Respect, Team Work) and exhibiting these values through the COVID-19 outbreak. Our educators will work in partnership with families to keep our students positively engaged socially, emotionally and academically.
Alternate Enrichment Learning Opportunities: During the school closure period, there will be varied opportunities and resources for students to reinforce skills that have already been taught and to engage with their teachers. On Monday, you can expect to receive a communication from your building principal who will share the learning enrichment templates for this week. You can also expect to receive communication from your child(ren)s teacher(s).
The enrichment learning opportunities are optional and not required for students to complete.We highly recommend that students engage in the enrichment learning activities to support the maintenance of skills that have been developed. There will not be any grades given for work done during the school closure period. Grades will only be given for work that was completed and submitted on or before March 12, 2020.

Families should pull up to the entrance of the school and pop open your trunk or let down the back passenger side window. 
Please do not exit your vehicle, a staff member will place the meals in your vehicle. 

Central Office and School Building Access: 
All buildings will remain closed to the public during the school closure period. Central office and school administrators will maintain a modified schedule to adhere to the social distancing requirement. Beginning Monday, March 23, Central Office will be open 8am-1pm; Monday-Wednesday-Friday. Central Office staff and Principals will work remotely Tuesdays and Thursdays. 

The custodial staff are adhering to a rigorous cleaning, sanitizing and disinfecting schedule to ensure that all buildings are free of germs and any potential contamination. 

Building principals have developed a process and will collaborate with the faculty and staff to allow access so that the faculty and staff can retrieve needed materials from their classrooms/offices. Mr. ORourke and Mr. Olsen have already collaborated with the music and performing arts departments to contact students/families so that students can retrieve their instruments. They will follow the same process as the technology and food service departments. Elementary principals will do the same. 

Social Distancing: 
We have received a number of questions and concerns about social distancing and what this means for you and your family. Social distancing general means avoiding group settings, large gatherings and maintaining physical distancing from others. This applies to all settings including playgrounds and sports fields. As a result, I am asking that you support our efforts to keep students from gathering on sports fields and playgrounds during this time. We understand and encourage getting outside and getting fresh air and exercise but ask that it be done responsibly and by following the social distancing guidelines. 

Communication Expectations: 
Each week, Superintendents meet remotely with the Commissioner of Education and other state officials. Therefore, you can expect to receive an update from the Superintendents office at least weekly. 

All current and past information related to COVID-19 and the school closure can be accessed here. You can access resources to Keep Learning Alive in SPS here. 

We understand that we are in a time where there is much uncertainty and encourage you to seek valid information from the Massachusetts Department of Health, the Sharon Health Department and the Centers for Disease Control.
